This is a set of verbs for doing simple math with PWL files.   It is
essentially the same algorithm used inside Post for PWL arithmetic.

The algorithm for cross-interpolating the files is interesting.  If the
PWL files are defined at different independent variable (iv) times, the
programs perform a cross interpolation of both files such that the
output wavefrom is defined at all iv points of either file.  The
algorithm decides which file to pull the next data point from based on a
state maching that compares last two points read from each file. 

sig.a and sig.b are two test PWL files.

You can plot them with 
	
	cat sig.a sig.b | pd

You can add the average of the two files to the plot with:

	add sig.a sig.b | pd  -n

similarly:

	sub sig.a sig.b  | pd  -n	; sig.b subtracted from sig.a
	min sig.a sig.b  | pd  -n	; minimum of the two sigs
	max sig.a sig.b  | pd  -n	; maximum of the two sigs
	avg sig.a sig.b  | pd  -n	; average of the two sigs
	mult sig.a sig.b | pd  -n	; the two sigs multiplied
	div sig.a sig.b  | pd  -n	; sig.a divided by sig.b

There are also a few scripts for querying a PWL

	 xcross [options] < file ; print both rising and falling zero crossings
         xcrossp [options] < file ; print only rising zero crossings
	 xcrossn [options] < file ; print only falling zero crossings
	    -n <N> ; only print the nth crossing (default=ALL)
	    -v <volts> ; set crossing voltage (default=0)
	    -h ; print this usage message

         yvalue [options] < file # print the y value of the waveform at given time
            -t <time> # specify the sample time
            -h #print this usage message

And a few other scripts to modify PWL in various ways

	lam "PWL1" "PWL2" ; output three columns with common time scale

        delay [options] < file ; create a time-delayed pwl file
	  -t time ; set time delay (0=default)
	  -h ; print this usage message

	eye [options] < PWL ; munge time axis to provide an eye-diagram scope display
	  -u <time> ; set UI time (1)
	  -w <width> ; scan width in UI (3)
	  -h ; print this usage message

	scope [options] < PWL ; munge time axis to provide a triggered scope display\n
	  -t [0,1,-1] ; set trigger mode (1=rising, -1=falling, 0=both ($MODE)\n
	  -u <time>  ; set UI time ($UI)\n
	  -v <volts> ; set crossing voltage ($VOLTAGE)\n
	  -w <width> ; scan width in UI ($WIDTH)\n
	  -h         ; print this usage message\n"

	warp "PWL1" "PWL2" ; at each point in time, warp PWL1 time axis by the value of PWL2
